  <content>
    <title>Regulatory Compliance 2026</title>

    <summary>Accessibility regulation landscape shifted April 2026 (ADA Title II Final Rule → WCAG 2.1 AA), June 2025 (EU Accessibility Act effective date), and ongoing (AODA, Section 508). Map your product surfaces (website, native app, kiosk, e-book) to applicable regulations. Document conformance against WCAG 2.1 AA minimum. Publish an accessibility statement with dated testing methodology, feedback channel, and remediation commitment. Schedule audits at least annually; flag every major release for incremental audit. Treat WCAG 2.2 AA as the design baseline even where 2.1 is the legal minimum — gap-closing later is more expensive. Avoid overlay widgets that claim to "auto-fix" a11y; they have lost cases in US courts. Train content authors — most violations enter via CMS, not engineering.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Accessibility is now explicitly mandated by law across the US, EU, Canada, and Australia. Non-compliance exposes organizations to litigation, regulatory penalties, and brand damage. The April 2026 ADA Title II Final Rule set WCAG 2.1 AA as the federal accessibility standard; the EU Accessibility Act (EAA, effective June 2025) mandates EN 301 549 (which references WCAG 2.1 AA) for e-commerce, banking, transport, and e-books. Section 508 (US federal procurement) and AODA (Ontario, Canada) add regional specificity.</p>
      <p>Automated tools catch only 30–40% of WCAG issues; human + assistive-technology (AT) testing is required. "Compliance" claims without documented testing methodology increase legal exposure. Courts view absence of an accessibility statement as evidence of bad faith.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch a11y audit for a US/EU public-facing site or app (post-ADA April 2026 / EAA June 2025).</item>
        <item>Drafting an accessibility statement and conformance documentation per WCAG 2.1/2.2 AA.</item>
        <item>Mapping product surface area (web, native, kiosk, e-book) to specific regulations (ADA Title II, EAA, AODA, Section 508).</item>
        <item>Quarterly/annual a11y audit cycle planning + remediation backlog.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Implementation-level a11y fixes — see `accessibility-evaluation`, `wcag-22-compliance`, `testing-with-assistive-technology`.</item>
        <item>Privacy/data regulation (GDPR, CCPA, HIPAA) — different methodology.</item>
        <item>Pure design tokens / visual contrast — covered in `accessibility-first-design`.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="regulatory-landscape">
      <p>Key regulations by region, deadline, and conformance standard:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Inventory all product surfaces (site, app, kiosk, e-book) and map each to applicable regulations: ADA Title II (US, WCAG 2.1 AA, effective April 2026), EAA (EU, EN 301 549 / WCAG 2.1 AA, effective June 2025), AODA (Ontario, WCAG 2.0 AA, now), Section 508 (US Federal, WCAG 2.0 AA, now). Identify the earliest deadline and responsible team. Document applicability per surface.</statement>
        <rationale>Regulatory applicability varies by jurisdiction and product type (e-commerce vs. government vs. public sector). Mapping forces explicit decisions about which surfaces fall under which rules. The earliest deadline is your constraint.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Regulatory applicability matrix">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Product Surface | US ADA | EU EAA | AODA | Section 508
────────────────┼────────┼────────┼──────┼────────────
Website         | YES    | YES    | YES  | if fed contract
Native app      | YES    | Limited| YES  | if fed contract
  (iOS/Android) |        |(mobile)|(web) |
Kiosk           | YES    | YES    | YES  | if fed
E-book          | NO     | YES*   | YES* | varies
                |        |(*scope)|(web) |

Earliest deadline: EU EAA June 2025 → Website + E-book
Responsible team: Product + Legal (compliance checkpoint)
        ]]></code>
        <note>EU EAA has the earliest mandate; website and e-book surfaces are in scope.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="ADA Title II vs. EAA scope">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
ADA Title II (US, April 2026)
├─ Applies to all state/local government and public entities
├─ Websites + native apps + kiosks
└─ Standard: WCAG 2.1 AA

EAA (EU, June 2025)
├─ Applies to: e-commerce, banking, transport, e-books
├─ Excluded: microenterprises, very small businesses
└─ Standard: EN 301 549 v3.2.1 (references WCAG 2.1 AA)

Section 508 (US Federal, ongoing)
├─ Applies to: US federal agencies + federal contractors
└─ Standard: WCAG 2.0 AA (legacy; upgrading to 2.1 soon)

AODA (Ontario, Canada, ongoing)
├─ Applies to: public sector + private orgs >10 employees
└─ Standard: WCAG 2.0 AA (web); Level AA (native)
        ]]></code>
        <note>Scope varies by jurisdiction. No single "universal" standard; regional specificity matters.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Regulations are jurisdictional; this methodology gives a US/EU snapshot but ignores UK Equality Act, Japanese JIS X 8341, Australian DDA, etc.</description>
        <reason>If your product serves Australia, Japan, or UK, research those standards separately. This methodology covers the largest markets (US + EU); add region-specific rules as your user base expands.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>The compliance checklist is necessary but not sufficient — passes don't preclude lawsuits.</description>
        <reason>Conformance certification provides evidence of good-faith effort, but does not guarantee immunity. Courts focus on whether the product is actually usable by disabled users, not checkbox compliance.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>WCAG 2.1 AA is a floor; some agencies (US federal contracts, EU public sector) require 2.2 AA or AAA in places.</description>
        <reason>High-risk surfaces (election sites, healthcare portals, financial services) may have stricter requirements. Check your sector's guidance.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="wcag-baseline">
      <p>WCAG (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines) is the industry standard. Conform to WCAG 2.1 AA minimum; aim for 2.2 AA to future-proof.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat WCAG 2.2 AA as the design baseline even where 2.1 AA is the legal minimum. Automated checkers (axe-core, pa11y, Lighthouse) catch only 30–40% of WCAG issues. Human + assistive-technology (AT) testing with real users is mandatory. Never claim conformance without documented testing (manual + automated + AT user sessions).</statement>
        <rationale>2.2 AA is the newer standard; upgrading later is more expensive than designing to it now. Automated tools miss context-dependent failures (form labels, reading order, focus management) that only humans testing with AT catch. Courts scrutinize "conformance" claims without testing evidence.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Documented testing methodology (excerpt)">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
We test the website for accessibility conformance against WCAG 2.1 AA.

Testing methodology:
- Automated: axe-core + pa11y-ci on every staging deployment
- Manual: Heuristic walkthrough (WCAG-EM) monthly + per release
- AT: Monthly sessions with 2–3 screen-reader users (JAWS, NVDA)
  and 1–2 magnifier users (ZoomText, Magnifier)
- User feedback: Contact form accessible via 3 channels (web, email, tty)

Remediation: Issues are triaged by WCAG success criterion and
fixed within 30 days (critical) / 90 days (non-critical). This
statement is updated quarterly.

Last audit: 2026-04-28
Next audit: 2026-07-28
        ]]></code>
        <note>Dated, specific, and auditable. Courts view this as good-faith effort.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Vague conformance claim">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
"We are committed to accessibility."

(No mention of WCAG version, testing methodology, or feedback channel.
Vague, unverifiable, increases legal risk.)
        ]]></code>
        <note>Avoid vague claims. Specificity (WCAG 2.1 AA, tested with AT users) is a legal defense.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>"Statement published" can be a false-comfort metric — wrong claims of conformance increase legal exposure.</description>
        <reason>An accessibility statement claiming WCAG 2.1 AA conformance without evidence of testing is worse than no statement (it's evidence of intent to deceive). Stake claims to actual testing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="accessibility-statement">
      <p>Publish an accessibility statement on your website (linked from footer or contact page). It must include conformance claim, testing methodology, and remediation contact.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Publish a dated accessibility statement that declares WCAG version + level, describes the testing methodology (manual, automated, AT users), provides a feedback channel (email, form, phone, TTY), and commits to remediation timeline. Update the statement quarterly or after major releases. Require legal/compliance review before publication.</statement>
        <rationale>Dated statement shows good-faith effort and provides legal protection. Methodology specificity (not vague "we test") is critical for litigation defense. Feedback channel and commitment to remediation demonstrate ongoing care. Legal review prevents overstatement.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Accessibility statement (template)">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
## Accessibility Statement

[Company Name] is committed to ensuring digital accessibility.
We test the [Product Name] website and mobile app for accessibility
conformance against the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)
2.1 Level AA.

### Testing Methodology

This product is tested for accessibility using:
- Automated tools: axe-core, pa11y, Lighthouse
- Manual heuristic evaluation: WCAG-EM methodology
- Assistive technology users: Screen-reader (JAWS, NVDA),
  magnification (ZoomText), voice control (Dragon NaturallySpeaking)

Testing is conducted monthly and on all major releases.

### Conformance Status

We aim for full WCAG 2.1 AA conformance. Known issues are listed
in our Accessibility Issues Registry [link].

### Feedback & Remediation

If you encounter accessibility barriers, please contact us:
- Web form: [link]
- Email: accessibility@[company].com
- Phone: [phone number]
- TTY: [TTY number]

We commit to responding within 5 business days and remediate
critical issues within 30 days.

Last updated: 2026-04-28
        ]]></code>
        <note>Specific, dated, auditable. Shows good-faith effort and provides legal protection.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Use agents to inventory surfaces, map regulations, and generate remediation backlogs. Require legal-review checkpoint on the accessibility statement.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Drive Claude to inventory product surfaces (sites, apps, e-books, kiosks), map each to applicable regulations, and produce a remediation backlog ordered by deadline + risk. A second agent runs axe-core / pa11y / Lighthouse against staging URLs and merges results into the backlog. A legal-review checkpoint validates the accessibility statement language before publication.</statement>
        <rationale>Automation scales regulatory mapping and backlog generation. But legal sign-off on the statement (the public-facing artifact) prevents overstatement and liability.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>LLMs paraphrase WCAG success criteria inaccurately — quote the spec, don't summarize. "WCAG 2.1 AA" vs. "EN 301 549" overlap heavily but diverge on hardware/IT — agents conflate them. Always check the specific regulation's referenced version. Auto-generated statements often claim more conformance than evidence supports — legal exposure. Agents should not produce final "we are compliant" copy — only "we test against WCAG 2.1 AA and remediate" hedged language.</statement>
        <rationale>AI misquotes regulations and conflates standards. Statements without legal review are liability. Stay conservative: "we test and remediate" is defensible; "we are compliant" is a lawsuit magnet.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <note>Recommended subagents: `faion-accessibility-specialist-agent` (or generic) — translate regulation requirements into testable acceptance criteria. `faion-ux-researcher-agent` — plan AT user testing panels (screen reader, switch, magnifier, voice). Custom `compliance-mapper` — given product manifest + regulations, output applicability matrix + deadlines.</note>

      <example type="good" title="Prompt: Regulatory inventory">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Given <product surfaces JSON> and <region list>, output:
- Regulation applicability matrix (surface × regulation).
- WCAG version + level required per cell.
- Earliest deadline + responsible team.
- Top 5 a11y risks per surface.
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Prompt: Remediation backlog">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Given <axe JSON output> + <regulation map>, generate
remediation tickets sorted by (regulation severity × user impact).
Each ticket: WCAG SC, surface, repro steps, suggested fix, deadline.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="audit-cycle">
      <p>Schedule accessibility audits at least annually; flag every major release for incremental audit.</p>

      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Schedule audits at least annually; flag every major release for an incremental audit. Document the testing methodology (manual + automated + AT users) — "we ran axe" is not a defense. Train content authors — most violations enter via CMS, not engineering. Avoid overlay widgets that "auto-fix" a11y; they have lost cases in US courts.</statement>
        <rationale>Annual minimum keeps the bar fresh. Major releases often introduce violations (new components, new copy). Documented methodology is a legal defense. CMS content is the biggest source of new violations; training scales compliance. Overlays are liabilities — they introduce their own a11y issues and courts reject them as non-compliant.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Annual audit calendar">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
2026 Accessibility Audit Calendar
├─ Q1 (Jan–Mar): Annual full audit (manual + AT + axe)
├─ Q2 (Apr–Jun): Post-major-release incremental audit
├─ Q3 (Jul–Sep): CMS content audit + author training refresh
├─ Q4 (Oct–Dec): Year-end statement update + next-year planning
└─ On-demand: Within 1 week of any major feature release

Responsible: Product + Accessibility team + Legal (statement)
        ]]></code>
        <note>Regular cadence prevents drift. Tie audits to product calendar.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-services">
      <p>Automated tooling catches 30–40% of WCAG issues. Use in combination with human testing.</p>

      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
CLI Tools
─────────
axe-core / @axe-core/cli
  – Automated WCAG 2.1/2.2 checks
  – npm i -g @axe-core/cli

pa11y / pa11y-ci
  – Batch URL audits in CI
  – npm i -g pa11y-ci

lighthouse
  – Includes a11y category, JSON output
  – npm i -g lighthouse

accessibility-insights-cli
  – Microsoft AC tooling, FastPass
  – accessibilityinsights.io

arc-toolkit (TPGi)
  – Manual + automated, exportable
  – tpgi.com

nu-html-checker (vnu)
  – Validate HTML which feeds a11y issues
  – validator.github.io

SaaS Services
─────────────
Deque axe DevTools
  – SaaS + OSS | Industry standard; CI integrations

Siteimprove
  – SaaS | Crawl-based monitoring; statement generator

Level Access
  – SaaS | Enterprise; legal-review-grade reports

Tenon.io
  – SaaS | Single-page or batch URL checks

WAVE (WebAIM)
  – SaaS | Free; manual UI; useful for spot checks

Fable
  – SaaS | Recruit AT users for moderated testing

Applause Accessibility
  – SaaS | Crowd of disabled testers
      ]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="pa11y-ci-example">
      <p>Example CI runner to catch WCAG issues on every deploy (≤50 lines):</p>

      <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail
URLS=( "https://example.com/" "https://example.com/checkout" "https://example.com/account" )
THRESHOLD=0   # zero allowed errors at 2.1 AA before launch
TOTAL=0
for url in "${URLS[@]}"; do
  out=$(pa11y --standard WCAG2AA --reporter json "$url" || true)
  count=$(jq 'length' <<<"$out")
  echo "::group::$url ($count issues)"
  jq -r '.[] | "\(.code)  \(.selector)  \(.message)"' <<<"$out"
  echo "::endgroup::"
  TOTAL=$((TOTAL + count))
done
echo "TOTAL=$TOTAL"
[ "$TOTAL" -le "$THRESHOLD" ]
      ]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Treat WCAG 2.2 AA as the design baseline even where 2.1 is the legal minimum. Publish a dated accessibility statement linking to a feedback channel; courts and regulators view absence as bad faith. Document the testing methodology (manual + automated + AT users); "we ran axe" is not a defense. Schedule audits at least annually; flag every major release for an incremental audit. Avoid overlay widgets that "auto-fix" a11y; they have lost cases in US courts. Train content authors — most violations enter via CMS, not engineering.</statement>
        <rationale>Future-proofing saves rework. Dated statement + feedback = legal protection. Methodology = defense against litigation. Regular audits prevent drift. Overlays are proven liabilities. CMS training scales compliance beyond engineering.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>LLMs paraphrase WCAG success criteria inaccurately — quote the spec, don't summarize. "WCAG 2.1 AA" vs. "EN 301 549" overlap heavily but diverge on hardware/IT — agents conflate them. Always check the specific regulation's referenced version. Auto-generated statements often claim more conformance than evidence supports — legal exposure. Human-in-loop checkpoint required: legal/compliance reviewer signs off on every public statement. ADA/EAA dates change via guidance updates — pull current dates from official sources, not the model's memory.</statement>
        <rationale>AI misquotes standards and conflates regulations. Unchecked statements are liability. Legal review prevents exposure. Dates shift via official updates; use primary sources.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

